1. Data Preprocessing¶

The first preprocessing step assumes data is acquired from a relational database.
Steps in this section can be handled there or in an environment similar to this one.
In [2]:
# Child table from .feather file
original_raw_lgc_feather_df = pd.read_feather('TEST_order_item_11-11-22.feather')


# Child dataset from csv, contains new customer_id column
test_df = pd.read_csv('TEST_order_item_11-11-22.csv', parse_dates = True)


# Merge new column to order_item table from .feather file
extracted_col = test_df["customer_id"]
  
original_raw_lgc_feather_df = original_raw_lgc_feather_df.join(extracted_col)


# New order_item table
lgc_order_item_df = original_raw_lgc_feather_df


# digital_card_orders table
lgc_digital_card_order_df = pd.read_csv('TEST_digital_card_orders_11-11-22.csv', parse_dates = True)


# Merge order_item and digital_card_order tables into one dataframe
left_merged_df = pd.merge(lgc_digital_card_order_df, lgc_order_item_df, how = 'left', on = ['id'])


# Set the index of the new dataframe to the created_date of dco table
transformed_lgc_df = left_merged_df.set_index(pd.DatetimeIndex(left_merged_df['created_date_x']))


# Set the card status to "Captured"
transformed_lgc_df = transformed_lgc_df.loc[transformed_lgc_df['status'].isin(['Captured'])]


# Ensure all dates are captured, all downstream analysis will utilize this variable
lgc_ground_truth_df = transformed_lgc_df.loc['2021-01-01':'2022-01-31']
lgc_ground_truth_df.drop(columns = 'Unnamed: 0', axis = 1, inplace = True)

3. Average/Overall Product Denomination by Quarter, Month, Week & Day¶

Downsampling the data to get a better view¶

Average and overall views provide meaningful insights¶

    Insights:
        More or less, product denomination variance is consistent at the beginning and end of the month
        Huge spikes in the beginning and end of March, maybe some international holiday, or sale/discount on products
        Huge dip in April
        Huge spikes in July, October, November, December during Christmas/New Years. Seasonality on fall/winter months
         seems obvious, not sure about the summer

Seasonal Trend Decomposition Analysis¶

Insights:
   Important step in the process to see: 
     - What the general trend should be
     - Understand the strength of the trend
     - What kind of forecast accuracy can be expected
     - Identify any interesting behavior in the seasonal component of the trend

   The data is stationary
     - Important factor in determining predictability

   Data is robust to error, there is predictability we can leverage   
   Peak sales around a time of year, confirmed with a decomposition of the yearly trend
   BLUE line denotes actual trend/seasonality, red line denotes the possible margin of error

5. Customer Segmentation¶

Calculate RFM score and then identify any patterns within the customer base¶

    - The RFM score is a ranking used to segment customers based on customer normalized recency, 
      frequency, monetary values. 

           Recency - Number of days since the last purchase
           Frequency - Number of transactions made over a given period
           Monetary - Amount spent over a given period of time

 We do not know if there are additional dependent variables between customers, but this 
  method can help us determine if there are

Customer Spending Habit & Engagement Clusters¶

X axis denotes how much customers spend, y axis denotes the frequency at which they spend 
The higher on the x axis, the more they spend, higher on the y axis the more frequently they spend

Insights:
    Customers in the first three buckets spend frequently, but they do not spend very much
    Customers in the next bucket spend almost as frequently and they spend more
    Customers in the last two buckets spend a lot but not as frequently
    Customers are evenly distributed until they start spending a lot more
    This can be further broken down to see the different segments between customers using different variables in the X 
     and y axis. Eg. status, country, a comparison of products and prices 

    Something like this could be useful to profile customers and help generate ideas on how to keep low 
     frequency customers more engaged at higher levels and how to keep high spending customers more engaged, maybe 
     there are other factors to consider

6. Forecasting Product Denomination¶

XGBoost with Bayesian Optimization¶

Insights:
     Due to seasonality, there may be a spike in product denomination starting in the fall until sometime in December 

     There is more prediction performance to gain through acquiring more data. Typically the further out you try to 
      predict, especially on small data, its going to be harder to predict with accuracy. One to two hours is going to 
      be easier to predict than one to two years. If more data does not exist, might be possible to use synthetic data

     The feature importance chart shows the importance of each feature in the dataset by each features statistical 
      significance  

Observations:
     I'm unsure about the casuality between the independent variables and the dependent variable(defer to SMEs)
     Seems like the model is good at capturing the average activity, struggles a bit with large peaks. More tuning and 
      adding more features without adding more data could produce moderately better predictions

Feature Correlation Heatmaps¶

Overall distribution of product denomination has strong variations. The Spearman correlation is used to quantify the 
relationship between variables because it is not sensitive to outliers. The further away the correlation coefficient is 
from zero in either direction indicates how highly correlated(positive) or not correlated(negative) the strength of the 
relationship is between two variables. Values approaching 70% risk multicollinearity. 

Observations:
    After feature engineering there are more independent variables which equals more predictive power
    The correlation between lag features: 'product denom difference', 'sales', 'product denom mean' have high  
     pairwise correlation, would probably introduce overfitting and must be removed
    Seasonality is apparent

Insights (should be mined further by SMEs):
    The more products you sell, the higher the sales (which is trivial)
    Maybe customers care about product inventory and variation
    Customers really care about how their products are delivered, where customers are from drive this to some extent

    Maybe there's minimal support here for my "how many recipients are senders" hypothesis
       - Email marketing during certain periods of time tailored to each cluster to boost awareness & cross-sell 
         to recipients who are also senders might be a good strategy
